CASSELMAN WINDPOWER LLC
1. Availability: Casselman Windpower LLC (“Casselman Windpower”) makes electric energy and capacity available under this FERC electric tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below. Casselman Windpower also makes available, to any purchaser, ancillary services except as prohibited below: a. New England. Casselman Windpower offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. b. PJM. Casselman Windpower offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. c. New York. Casselman Windpower offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. d. California. Casselman Windpower offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. e. MISO. Casselman Windpower offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. f. Southwest Power Pool. Casselman Windpower offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (“SPP”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. g. Third Party Ancillary Services. Casselman Windpower offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider’s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability: This tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity and ancillary services by Casselman Windpower at market-based rates. 3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Casselman Windpower. 4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Casselman Windpower. 5. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Casselman Windpower shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Casselman Windpower's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Casselman Windpower to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Casselman Windpower's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Casselman Windpower's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: In Casselman Windpower LLC, Letter Order, Docket No. ER07-254-000 (Dec. 29, 2006), Casselman Windpower received (i) waiver of the accounting and reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101, and 141, with the exception of Sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subparts B and C, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket approval under Part 34. 7. Seller Category: Casselman Windpower is a Category 1 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a), in the Central, Northwest, Southeast and Southwest Regions and in the Southwest Power Pool. Casselman Windpower is a Category 2 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a), in the Northeast Region. 8. Effective Date: This tariff is effective upon the date specified by the Commission.

46 COMMON FACILITIES OWNERSHIP AND USE AGREEMENT
This COMMON FACILITIES OWNERSHIP AND USE AGREEMENT (Agreement), dated as of ________________, 2024 (the Execution Date), is entered into by and between CASSELMAN WINDPOWER, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Casselman), SUMMIT SOLAR PA, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Summit), and AURORA SOLAR LLC, an Oregon limited liability company (Aurora). RECITALS
A. Casselman has developed, and currently owns and operates, the Casselman Wind Project. B. The Casselman Wind Project includes an approximately 0.01 mile 115 kV transmission line designed and constructed to carry the electrical output of the Casselman Wind Project, and with potential excess capacity to carry all or a portion of the electrical output of Subsequent Project(s), from the Additional Common Facilities in the Casselman Wind Project Substation to the Interconnection Point at the Lick Run Substation. C. Summit is developing and will construct, own, and operate Summit Solar Project on sites located in the immediate vicinity of the Casselman Wind Project, which will benefit from use of the Gen-Tie Line and other Common Facilities. D. Affiliates of Casselman, Summit and/or Aurora may develop Subsequent Projects on sites located in the immediate vicinity of the Casselman Wind Project, which Subsequent Projects may benefit from the use of various facilities corridors within the Casselman Wind Land, and which Subsequent Projects may benefit from use of the Gen-Tie Line and other Common Facilities as and to the extent permitted by this Agreement. E. The purpose of this Agreement is to document the agreement of the Parties as to (1) the joint ownership and use of the Gen-Tie Line, (2) the installation and use of metering equipment to (a) facilitate the interconnection and operation of the Summit Solar Project and (b) physically and separately measure the output from the Casselman Wind Project and the Summit Solar Project in order to appropriately allocate revenues from such output to such Projects, (3) the shared use of the Common Facilities, for the mutual benefit of the Casselman Wind Project and Subsequent Project(s) (including the Summit Solar Project), as well as various related rights and responsibilities, and (4) the terms and conditions for Subsequent Projects to join this Agreement for purposes of sharing in the use of the Common Facilities. F. Capitalized terms used in these Recitals and not otherwise defined have the meanings stated in Section 1.1 below. AGREEMENT

ARTICLE 2 : SUBSEQUENT PROJECT; JOINT OWNERSHIP OF COMMON FACILITIES; SHARED USE RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Interconnection of Subsequent Project. The interconnection of the Summit Solar Project, any additional Subsequent Project, and construction and installation of any Additional Common Facilities, shall be subject to the following terms and conditions:
(a) Rights of Summit and Aurora; Joinder of Subsequent Projects. Effective as of the Execution Date, Summit is a Party and the Summit Solar Project constitutes a Subsequent Project. Unless Aurora becomes an Owner in accordance with the terms of this Agreement, (i) Aurora shall not be an Owner and shall not have any ownership interest in this Agreement, and (ii) Auroras rights under this Agreement shall be limited to the matters expressly set forth herein with respect to a Party generally, but shall exclude all rights of an Owner with respect to the Common Facilities, including pursuant to Article V hereunder. As a condition to any project becoming a Subsequent Project under this Agreement, the owner of such project shall execute and deliver a Joinder Agreement and thereafter comply with all terms and conditions of this Agreement applicable to it as a Subsequent Party and its Subsequent Project. Aurora, Casselman or Summit, as applicable, shall give written notice to the other Parties of Auroras, Casselmans or Summits, as applicable, desire to join any third party as a Subsequent Party pursuant to this Section 2.1(a), and the Parties and such third party shall have thirty (30) days after such notice to enter into a Joinder Agreement (such execution date being the Joinder Effective Date). Upon the occurrence of the Sharing Effective Date with respect to any such Subsequent Project for which the total capacity of the Gen-Tie Line becomes allocated to Projects in accordance with the terms of this Agreement, all rights of Aurora under this Agreement, including this Section 2.1(a), shall terminate and thereafter Aurora shall no longer be a Party to this Agreement.
(b) Interconnection Plans. Following the Execution Date (with respect to Summit) or execution of its Joinder Agreement (with respect to any other Subsequent Project), each Subsequent Party shall provide Casselman with the proposed plans, engineering drawings, and other requirements with respect to the interconnection of such Subsequent Partys Project, including specifications regarding any additional assets proposed to be included in the Common Facilities (Additional Common Facilities) and the Subsequent Project Facilities of such Subsequent Party, as well as such Subsequent Partys proposed Projects nameplate capacity, schedule, and needs for interconnection to the Interconnection Point, and such additional information regarding such Subsequent Partys interconnection plans as Casselman may reasonably request (the Interconnection Plans). In addition, such Subsequent Party shall also designate in such Interconnection Plans any Casselman Real Property Interests and the areas of proposed use of any portions of the Casselman Land (including the Casselman Substation Property to the extent contemplated herein). Such Subsequent Party shall prepare a map or mark-up of the Casselman as-built ALTA survey identifying and depicting generally each area of the Casselman Land that such Subsequent Party proposes to use for the installation, operation, use, maintenance, replacement and removal of underground and/or overhead collector lines and related equipment to transmit electrical energy generated by energy conversion systems comprising part of its Subsequent Project to the Interconnection Point (Proposed Casselman Land Usage), provided that such lines and equipment shall only be installed in locations that do not unreasonably interfere with the access to, or operation, maintenance or repair of, the Casselman Wind Facilities and are otherwise located in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice (the Casselman Land Use Condition). Further, with respect to the Summit Solar Project (as the first Subsequent Project to be constructed under this Agreement), Summit shall include in the Interconnection Plans general depictions of each area of the Casselman Wind Land subject to the Casselman Wind Real Property Interests proposed to be included as Shared Premises (and which shall be Proposed Casselman Wind Land Usage subject to the terms hereof).
(c) Engineering Confirmation. Prior to proceeding with construction of any Additional Common Facilities or modification of any Common Facilities required for a Subsequent Project, the applicable Subsequent Party shall obtain Casselmans approval of the Interconnection Plans, which approval shall not be unreasonably withheld, delayed or conditioned, provided that the Interconnection Plans and any Proposed Casselman Land Usage for such Subsequent Project reasonably satisfy the Casselman Land Use Condition. To the extent so confirmed by Casselman as reasonably satisfying the Casselman Land Use Condition, the applicable Casselman Real Property Interests shall become Shared Real Property Documents. Upon request of any Party, the Parties shall then enter into an amendment or supplement to this Agreement upon satisfaction of the Casselman Land Use Condition by each Subsequent Project to add such Casselman Real Property Interests as Shared Real Property Documents that satisfy the Casselman Land Use Condition as confirmed by Casselman. Within ninety (90) days after the commercial operation date of each Subsequent Project, the applicable Subsequent Party shall cause an as-built ALTA survey to be prepared of its Subsequent Project Facilities constructed on Shared Premises consistent with the last sentence of Section 2.1(b) above and deliver such as-built survey to Casselman.
(d) Interconnection and Transmission Facilities. The Parties acknowledge that all planning, construction and installation of interconnection and transmission facilities required for each Subsequent Partys Project, including such upgrades and additional design or operational components as may be necessary with respect to any Additional Common Facilities, shall be constructed pursuant to Prudent Industry Practice, at the sole cost and expense of the applicable Subsequent Party and consistent with Subsequent Partys interconnection agreement. The Owners also agree to memorialize their agreement in writing regarding the specific plans for each Subsequent Partys interconnection facilities prior to construction of such facilities.
(e) Metering; Line Losses. Each Owner shall install one or more metering devices at its Project reasonably acceptable to the Administrative Owner and, as applicable, the Transmission Provider and PJM and shall permit the Administrative Owner to read the results of such metering device upon reasonable prior notice from the Administrative Owner. With respect to the Summit Solar Project specifically, Summit shall install the metering devices to separately meter the output from the Summit Solar Project and the Casselman Wind Project at the generating side of the shared 115 kV breaker (the Shared Metering Facilities), as required by the interconnection agreement for the Summit Solar Project and as shall be further described and detailed in the Interconnection Plans. To the extent practical, the metering devices for each Project shall be in equivalent/mirrored locations; if each Projects metering devices are not in equivalent/mirrored locations for any reason, the Administrative Owner and each Owner shall cause such metering devices to be calibrated to compensate and account for the electrical line and transformation loss differences resulting from the metering devices not being in equivalent/mirrored locations. The Owners agree that the Administrative Owner shall operate under and adhere to any regulatory or system protocol or other binding agreement, including each Owners interconnection agreement related to the allocation of shared meters. Any energy, and revenue attributable to the energy, produced or transmitted by a Project shall be only for the benefit of the Owner of such Project based on the amount of energy transmitted into the Common Facilities from such Owners Project, as adjusted for line losses on the Common Facilities in accordance with this Agreement. All incremental losses occurring on the Common Facilities shall be allocated solely to the Subsequent Projects, provided that each additional Subsequent Project after the Summit Solar Project shall be allocated all additional incremental losses attributable to the addition of the capacity of such Subsequent Project. All such incremental line losses shall be calculated in a manner that is reasonably acceptable to the Owners and appropriately assigns the incremental losses to each Subsequent Project consistent with the Transmission Providers and PJMs standards, tariff or business practices. In the event of any dispute regarding the calculation of losses, any Owner shall have the right to submit the dispute to an independent engineer reasonably acceptable to all Parties for review and the decision of such independent engineer shall be binding. The cost for review by any such independent engineer shall be a Shared Expense under this Agreement.
(f) Subsequent Project Cutover. Summit, for purposes of the Summit Solar Project, and each additional Subsequent Party by execution and delivery of a Joinder Agreement, acknowledges and agrees that the construction, installation, startup, testing, and related initial interconnection of the applicable Subsequent Partys interconnection and transmission facilities to the Common Facilities (with respect to each Subsequent Project, a Subsequent Project Cutover) may result in damage to Casselmans and prior Subsequent Partys property or persons and lost revenues associated with scheduled and/or unscheduled outages and/or curtailment of some or all of the energy production from the Casselman Wind Project or prior Subsequent Projects, including the cash value of any lost tax credits, on an After-Tax Basis, penalties imposed on Casselman or such prior Subsequent Project or damages payable by Casselman or such prior Subsequent Party to a power purchaser or the transmission service provider and any associated or related costs and/or expenses, including total payments lost for products (including energy, green attributes, capacity or other products) sold under any applicable purchase power agreement not generated and delivered, any resource adequacy or availability incentive or bonus payments lost, and any resource adequacy payment charges, minimum energy delivery obligation charges, or other penalties, costs or charges incurred, under any purchase power agreement, transmission tariff or otherwise (as applicable to each Subsequent Project, collectively, Subsequent Project Cutover Losses). All resulting Subsequent Project Cutover Losses shall be the sole responsibility of the applicable Subsequent Party owning the Subsequent Project to which such Subsequent Project Cutover Losses relate. As part of the process for interconnection of each Subsequent Partys Project, the Owners shall establish a protocol to reasonably minimize disruptions to the Casselman Wind Project and Projects of any prior Subsequent Parties during the construction and initial interconnection of such Subsequent Partys facilities to the Common Facilities. To the extent a Subsequent Party owes Casselman or any such prior Subsequent Party for any Subsequent Project Cutover Losses, such amounts shall be determined by Casselman or such prior Subsequent Owner, as applicable, in a commercially reasonable manner within thirty (30) days of completion of the Subsequent Project Cutover for such Subsequent Project which will be deemed to occur following the system operators approval of the commissioning for such Subsequent Project. Each Subsequent Party shall pay any Subsequent Project Cutover Losses owed to Casselman or such prior Subsequent Party within sixty (60) days of completion of the Subsequent Project Cutover for its Subsequent Project.
(g) Grid Connection and Other Costs. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, each Subsequent Party shall be solely responsible for the payment of any and all grid interconnection or other charges, registration costs, or other fees or costs related to the delivery of electrical energy generated by its Project to the Interconnection Point, including but not limited to, any such charges, fees or costs for scheduling, imbalance, or ancillary services; provided, however, that it is expressly understood and agreed that each Owner shall not request or receive any such services from any other Owner. Each Owner shall be responsible for any required modifications of the Transmission Providers Interconnection Facilities due to interconnecting their generation capacity to the Common Facilities and all costs related thereto.
(h) Further Assurances. Each Owner shall promptly take such action (including, but not limited to, the execution, acknowledgment, delivery and recordation of such separate deeds, assignments, bills of sale, and other documents and instruments (collectively, Shared Interest Conveyance Documents) as may reasonably be requested by any other Owner to effect, evidence or vest each Owners respective Ownership Interest in the Common Facilities or any portion thereof and its Shared Interests under Shared Real Property Documents, or to evidence the transfer by such other Owner of any of its Ownership Interest in the Common Facilities, including the transfer by any Subsequent Party to Casselman of its applicable Ownership Interest in any Additional Common Facilities constructed or installed by such Subsequent Party in accordance with the terms of this Agreement and its Shared Interest under any Shared Real Property Documents acquired by such Subsequent Party related thereto.
(i) Shared Expenses. From and after the Sharing Effective Date, each Subsequent Party shall bear its Sharing Ratio of the Shared Expenses. To the extent there is any provision in this Agreement that is, or appears to be, inconsistent with this paragraph, the terms of this paragraph shall control and govern any such provision.
(j) FirstEnergy. Administrative Owner shall provide notice to FirstEnergy of any request from a third party, or parties, who is not an Owner, to interconnect generation facilities to the Interconnection Customers Interconnection Facilities and coordinate with FirstEnergy to allow any third party or parties to use the Interconnection Facilities and to determine the allocation of costs in connection with the Interconnection Facilities pursuant to the Casselman Wind Interconnection Agreement and any other Subsequent Party interconnection agreement(s) within ninety (90) calendar days of receiving such request. 2.2 Joint Ownership and Use of Common Facilities. (a) Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the ownership of the Common Facilities shall be as follows:
(i) Summit Solar Project Sharing Effective Date; Ownership Interests. As of the Sharing Effective Date with respect to the Summit Project, subject to any required regulatory approvals (including any that may be required by FERC under Section 203 of the Federal Power Act, or an acceptance of any filings under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act), and upon and subject to the terms, conditions, restrictions and reservations set forth in this Agreement and in the Shared Real Property Documents, (A) Summit shall hold an undivided interest in the Common Facilities equal to the ratio of the actual installed nameplate capacity of the Summit Solar Project (up to a maximum of 100 MWac) to the total capacity of the Gen-Tie Line, and (B) Casselman shall retain an undivided interest in the Common Facilities equal to the ratio of all capacity of the Gen-Tie Line not allocated to the Summit Solar Project to the total capacity of the Gen-Tie Line (collectively, the Ownership Interests). For avoidance of doubt, Casselman shall own any and all Casselman Wind Project Facilities from time to time comprising the Cassselman Wind Project Substation. Administrative Owner shall communicate to FirstEnergy the Ownership Interests within thirty (30) calendar days of the Sharing Effective Date or any other changes to the Ownership Interests.
(ii) Automatic Termination. If the Sharing Effective Date has not occurred for the Summit Solar Project within ten (10) years after the Execution Date, then this Agreement shall automatically terminate and be of no further force and effect.
(b) Additional Subsequent Project Sharing Effective Date; Ownership Interests. As of the Sharing Effective Date with respect to any additional Subsequent Project occurring after the Sharing Effective Date of the Summit Solar Project, subject to any required regulatory filings or approvals (including any that may be required by FERC under Section 203 of the Federal Power Act, or an acceptance of any filings under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act), and upon and subject to the terms, conditions, restrictions and reservations set forth in this Agreement and in the Shared Real Property Documents:
(i) the Ownership Interest of such Subsequent Party shall be equal to the ratio of the lesser of (A) the actual installed nameplate capacity of the Subsequent Project of such Subsequent Party, and (B) the then-remaining capacity of the Gen-Tie Line not allocated to Casselman (after taking into account the adjustment to the Ownership Interest of Casselman Wind pursuant to clause (ii) below) and each other Subsequent Party whose Subsequent Project has achieved its Sharing Effective Date, to the total capacity of the Gen-Tie Line, and
(ii) the Ownership Interest of Casselman shall be adjusted to equal the greater of (A) the ratio of all capacity of the Gen-Tie Line not allocated to all Subsequent Parties whose Subsequent Project has achieved its Sharing Effective Date (based on the actual installed nameplate capacity of each such Subsequent Project) to the total capacity of the Gen-Tie Line, and (B) the ratio of the actual installed nameplate capacity of the Casselman Wind Project, to the total capacity of the Gen-Tie Line. The examples set forth in Schedule 2 attached hereto illustrate the intended manner in which Ownership Interests are calculated pursuant to this Section 2.2(b).
(c) Common Facilities Construction Requirements. No Subsequent Party shall begin actual construction of any Additional Common Facilities or modification of the Common Facilities until it has satisfied Sections 2.1(b)(e) of this Agreement. If a Subsequent Party has not begun actual construction or modification (and satisfaction of Sections 2.1(b)-(e) of this Agreement) within eighteen (18) months after the Sharing Effective Date with respect to its applicable Subsequent Project, (i) the Joinder Agreement with respect to such Subsequent Party shall automatically terminate, and (ii) the rights granted to such Subsequent Party under this Agreement shall automatically be returned to the Parties to this Agreement prior to such Subsequent Partys joinder.
(d) No Revenue or Profit Intended or Expected. The ownership structure stated in this Section 2.2 is not organized with the intention or expectation of producing revenue or making a profit from the operation of the Gen-Tie Line or other Common Facilities but merely as an ownership form through which the Owners can accomplish their purpose of owning, operating and making the Gen-Tie Line and other Common Facilities available for the use of the Owners in connection with their respective Projects. At no time shall the Gen-Tie Line or any other Common Facilities be used by any person other than an Owner. Subject to the rights of each Owner under Article 8 in the event of the possible sale or other disposition of its Ownership Interest in the Common Facilities, or under Article 8 in the event all or a portion of the Gen-Tie Line, Casselman Wind Project Substation or other Common Facilities is removed from service, the Owners do not expect to receive any material amount of revenue from such sale, disposition or removal from service.
(e) Use of Gen-Tie Line. Each Owner shall be entitled to use the Gen-Tie Line capacity to transmit electricity from the Project of such Owner to the Interconnection Point, in an amount up to its Ownership Interest multiplied by the Full Capacity of the Gen-Tie Line. Each Owner covenants that it will not at any time interconnect with the Gen-Tie Line electric generation facilities with an aggregate capacity that exceeds such Owners Ownership Interest multiplied by the Full Capacity of the Gen-Tie Line. If at any time the Administrative Owner advises the Owners that in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice the Gen-Tie Line temporarily must be curtailed to transmit at a rate lower than its Full Capacity, Casselmans right to utilize the Gen-Tie Line capacity for transmission of the electrical output of the Casselman Wind Project shall have priority over the rights of other Owners of the Gen-Tie Line for the full capacity of the Casselman Wind Project, and the other Owners shall curtail their use of the Gen-Tie Line capacity as follows: (i) the Owner of the Summit Solar Project shall fully curtail the Summit Solar Project with respect to the use of the Gen-Tie Line to the extent required to accommodate the full capacity of the Casselman Wind Project, and for all capacity of the Gen-Tie Line in excess of the capacity of the Casselman Wind Project, the Summit Solar Project Owners right to utilize the Gen-Tie Line capacity for transmission of the electrical output of the Summit Solar Project shall have priority over the rights of other Owners (other than Casselman) for the full capacity of the Summit Solar Project, and (ii) the other Owners shall fully curtail use of the Gen-Tie Line to the extent required to accommodate the aggregate capacity of the Casselman Wind Project and the Summit Solar Project, and for any capacity of the Gen-Tie Line in excess of such aggregate capacity of the Casselman Wind Project and the Summit Solar Project, the other Owners shall curtail use of the Gen-Tie Line pro-rata to their relative Ownership Interests, in each case, such curtailment to be in an amount equal to any reduction in total Gen-Tie Line capacity specified by the Administrative Owner, for such period as is specified as the period of necessary curtailment by the Administrative Owner. Administrative Owner will be responsible for coordinating operations of voltage control among the Casselman Wind Project and each Subsequent Project pursuant to Casselmans and each Subsequent Partys respective interconnection agreements. Casselman and each Subsequent Party will cooperate to manage voltage and respond to the Transmission Providers or PJMs operating instructions as required under their respective interconnection agreements.
(f) Gen-Tie Line Cost. No Subsequent Party shall be required to reimburse Casselman for such Subsequent Partys share of the costs and expenses Casselman incurred for the initial design, development and construction of the Gen-Tie Line as the Gen-Tie Line exists on the Effective Date. 2.3 Grant of Rights to Each Subsequent Party. Subject to the terms and conditions stated in this Agreement, including Sections 2.1, 2.2(c), and 13.16, and to the terms and conditions stated in each of the Shared Real Property Documents, Casselman hereby GRANTS, SUBLEASES, TRANSFERS, ASSIGNS and CONVEYS to each Subsequent Party, effective as of its applicable Sharing Effective Date, as owner of its Subsequent Project, for and during the Term, the following non-exclusive rights:
(a) to occupy and use the Shared Premises in accordance with the applicable Shared Real Property Documents and this Agreement;
(b) to use the Gen-Tie Line and all other Common Facilities in accordance with the applicable Shared Real Property Documents and applicable existing permits for such facilities, and this Agreement;
(c) to connect to and use the Common Communications Facilities; and
(d) to use all other access and communications easements and rights-of-way pursuant to the Shared Real Property Documents, together with the roads and paths of travel, and any gates, cattle guards or other improvements used in connection with same, that are used or useful for access to, between and among the applicable Subsequent Project, the Common Facilities, and any and all public roads, and which are located from time to time within the Shared Premises, that are reasonably required in connection with such non-exclusive use of the Common Communications Facilities, on condition that each Subsequent Party shall be responsible for any repairs or improvements to roads and any gates, cattle guards or other improvements used in connection with same within the Shared Premises that are necessitated by any construction activities on its Subsequent Project.
The Grants pursuant to Section 2.3(a) (d) shall be for the use and benefit of each Subsequent Party and, solely in connection with its Subsequent Project, for the use by such Subsequent Partys contractors, agents and employees. Casselman shall promptly take such action (including the execution, acknowledgment, delivery and recordation of one or more separate deeds, assignments, bills of sale, bifurcated leases, co-leases, subleases, easements, subeasements and other documents and instruments) as each Subsequent Party may reasonably request in order to further effect, evidence or vest such Subsequent Partys rights and interests under this Section 2.3.
2.4 Rights Subject to Shared Real Property Documents.
Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, all of the rights of each Subsequent Party under this Agreement are subject to the Shared Real Property Documents. This Agreement does not grant to any Subsequent Party any rights, interests or benefits greater than those provided to or permitted to Casselman under the Shared Real Property Documents; and this Agreement and each of the Grants are limited by and taken subject to the terms, conditions and provisions of the Shared Real Property Documents.
2.5 Condition to Exercise of Rights by Each Subsequent Party.
Each Subsequent Party shall be entitled to exercise its rights under the Grants only if (i) it has obtained all permits and other governmental approvals that are required and necessary for its Subsequent Project, and (ii) it gives written notice thereof to Casselman (with a copy to each affected Landowner, to the extent notice is required pursuant to the terms of any applicable Shared Real Property Document or Project Agreement). 2.6 Reservation of Rights by Casselman. (a) Use of Shared Premises. Casselman reserves the right to undertake any activities on the Shared Premises that are permitted by the Shared Real Property Documents (other than installation of any additional generation capacity to the Casselman Wind Project), to use and cross the Shared Premises and grant or assign use and crossing rights to other Persons as may be necessary in connection with the operation and maintenance of the Casselman Wind Project. Casselman may grant and convey non-exclusive rights in subeasements or subleases over the Shared Premises in favor of other Persons for purposes of the installation, use and operation of (i) transmission and/or communications facilities, and/or (ii) substations and/or interconnection or switching; in each case together with (A) all necessary or appropriate rights of way for access, ingress and egress to and from the Shared Premises and (B) the right in the transferee to grant or convey undivided or subordinate interests therein to other Persons as may be necessary in connection with the operation and maintenance of the Casselman Wind Project, so long as no such additional grants or conveyances materially interfere with each Subsequent Partys exercise of its Grants and rights under this Agreement.
(b) Amendment of Casselman Real Property Interests. Casselman hereby reserves the right, in its discretion, to amend, supplement or restate any of the Casselman Real Property Interests, without the consent of the Subsequent Parties, and each Subsequent Party hereby agrees (a) to any such amendment, supplement and restatement, and (b) that any such amendment, supplement or restatement shall automatically, and without the need for further documentation, be senior to the Grants and the rights of each Subsequent Party under this Agreement; provided, however, if any such Casselman Real Property Interests are Shared Real Property Documents or then designated and pending approval pursuant to Section 2.1 of this Agreement as Proposed Casselman Land Usage for a Subsequent Project, no such amendment, supplement or restatement shall have the effect of (i) materially increasing the duties or obligations of Subsequent Party under this Agreement or (ii) materially decreasing the rights or benefits given or afforded to Subsequent Party hereunder, without the written consent of the Subsequent Party. Casselman shall deliver a copy of any such amendment, supplement and restatement to such Subsequent Party related to any Proposed Casselman Land Usage or Shared Premises by such Subsequent Party. 2.7 Addition or Removal of Property. (a) Addition of Property. With respect to any part of any Project that is not part of the Common Facilities, the Owner of the Project shall have the right, at its sole cost and expense, to install one or more additional power transformers and all related equipment as part of its substation, revenue-quality meters and any additional meters that may be required by FirstEnergy, or any customer of such Owner, which in all cases shall at all times remain the sole property of the installing Owner.
(b) Removal of Property. Each Owner shall have the express right, at any time and in its sole discretion, to remove and/or replace any part of its Project, and all other property owned by such Owner, to the extent not included in the Common Facilities, prior to the expiration of the Term. If removal or replacement of any of such property will affect the safety or operation of the Common Facilities or any other Project, the Owner shall consult with and obtain the consent of each affected Owner before conducting the contemplated removal or replacement, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld or conditioned, and subject to compliance with reasonable requirements of any such other Owner in connection with the performance of such removal or replacement work to safeguard persons or property or minimize interference with operations of any such Owners Project. ARTICLE 3 : MAINTENANCE AND REPAIR 3.1 Operation and Maintenance of the Common Facilities.
Each Owner shall pay its allocated share of all Shared Expenses, as such costs are established and approved by the Owners Committee and the Administrative Owner, subject to each Owners rights of approval and disapproval as stated in Article 4. Each Owners allocation of such costs shall be proportional to its applicable Sharing Ratio.
ARTICLE 4 : MANAGEMENT OF COMMON FACILITIES
4.1 Administrative Owner.
Casselman shall be the Administrative Owner, subject to Casselmans right to resign as Administrative Owner. If Casselman (or any other entity) resigns as Administrative Owner, a successor Administrative Owner shall be selected by the Owners Committee. In addition, any Owner may call for a vote for removal of Administrative Owner for cause, which cause would include negligence that has a material adverse effect on the operation or maintenance of the Common Facilities. Consistent with the requirements of each Owners interconnection agreement, FirstEnergy will be notified, in writing by the Owners Committee, of any changes to the Administrative Owner within thirty (30) calendar days of a new Administrative Owner having been selected by the Owners Committee. 4.2 Powers and Duties of Administrative Owner. The Administrative Owner shall, as agent of and on behalf of each of the Owners:
(a) Operate and maintain (or provide for the operation and maintenance by a qualified third party) the Common Facilities, and maintain the Shared Premises (including all roads located thereon and any other portions of the Shared Premises upon which any Common Facilities are located), in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice, applicable laws, the terms of the Shared Real Property Documents, applicable interconnection agreements to which an Owner is a party, and commercially reasonable terms included in any insurance policies covering the Shared Premises upon which any Common Facilities are located and of which the Administrative Owner has received notice. In connection with such operation and maintenance, the Administrative Owner is authorized to interrupt service on the Gen-Tie Line and to require curtailments of Gen-Tie Line usage, in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice and in compliance with the terms of this Agreement. Administrative Owner will provide notice to FirstEnergy, the extent required by any Owners interconnection agreement, of any interruption of service or curtailment on the Gen-Tie Line as soon as practicable, and will be the primary point of contact responsible for responding to any directive from FirstEnergy to interrupt service;
(b) Prepare annual budgets and budget amendments as required with respect to the Common Facilities, and present such budgets and budget amendments for review and approval by the Owners Committee;
(c) Maintain up-to-date books and records related to the Common Facilities in accordance with generally acceptable accounting practices applicable to the electric utility industry and make such books and records available to each of the Owners upon the request of such Owner during the Administrative Owners regular business hours;
(d) Procure policies of insurance pursuant to Section 7.1;
(e) Perform, in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice, such other duties as may be specified by the Owners Committee;
(f) Execute such contracts and other documents as are necessary or appropriate to carry out the duties enumerated in Sections 4.2(a) through 4.2(d);
(g) Upon the request of any Owner, promptly provide to such Owner a statement, in such detail as may be reasonably requested by such Owner, of the amounts payable or reimbursable by such Owner pursuant to Section 4.4;
(h) Review any proposal by an Owner to interconnect generation facilities and confirm that the total capacity of all such generation facilities will not in the aggregate exceed such Owners Ownership Interest multiplied by the Full Capacity of the Gen-Tie Line. If the Administrative Owner determines that any Owner plans to interconnect generation facilities with the Gen-Tie Line in violation of such owners covenant in Section 2.1(c), or if any Owner fails to provide the Administrative Owner with sufficient information to make such determination, the Administrative Owner shall report such efforts to all other Owners and shall take all necessary actions to prevent such interconnection. Each Owner agrees to indemnify and hold the Administrative Owner harmless, and waives any claim against the Administrative Owner, for any action taken in good faith pursuant to this Section 4.2(h).
(i) Serve as the primary point of contact with FirstEnergy and PJM for required notices and/or all communications required for the day-to-day operation, regulatory requirements of the Common Facilities, and the coordination of the operation of Casselman and any Subsequent Project.
(j) Serve as the primary point of contact with FERC for required notices and filings under the Federal Power Act.
(k) Provide FirstEnergy with a copy of this Agreement and any material revisions to this Agreement within thirty (30) calendar days of the effective date of such revisions.
4.3 Authorized Expenditures. To the extent included in an annual budget or a budget amendment approved and effective pursuant to Sections 5.7 through 5.9 of this Agreement, as well as any additional cost incurred by the Administrative Owner and reimbursable under this Agreement, including all Shared Expenses, each of the Owners shall reimburse to the Administrative Owner an amount proportionate to its applicable Sharing Ratio (once any Subsequent Project Facilities have been installed, but only to the extent such Owner has interconnected any generation facilities to the Gen-Tie Line), of (i) the salaries, wages and related indirect and overhead costs properly allocable to the Common Facilities for the Administrative Owners personnel who perform the duties and obligations of the Administrative Owner pursuant to this Agreement; (ii) the reasonable payments by the Administrative Owner to third parties related to or in connection with the carrying out of the duties and obligations of the Administrative Owner pursuant to this Agreement; and (iii) the fixed (i.e. not revenue-related) portion of any payments pursuant to the Shared Real Property Documents (the Authorized Expenditures). The Administrative Owner will not be entitled to recovery with respect to any indirect costs or payments (including pursuant to any judgment, decree, injunction, order or decision by any governmental authority) incurred or owing by the Administrative Owner as a result of or in connection with any mistake, action, inaction or omission constituting gross negligence, fraud or willful or wanton misconduct by the Administrative Owner.
4.4 Reimbursement of Approved Costs. The invoicing and payment of any reimbursement pursuant to Section 4.3 shall be as follows:
(a) The Administrative Owner shall provide each Owner with an invoice no later than the tenth (10th) day of each month for Authorized Expenditures pursuant to Section 4.3 incurred during the previous month. The Administrative Owner shall furnish any receipts, documents, and other information in connection with each such statement as may reasonably show the basis for individual billings, charges, and cost computations, up to the date of such statement. The Administrative Owner shall promptly provide to each Owner such receipts, documents and other information in connection with each such statement as such Owner may reasonably request. Within thirty (30) days after receipt of each such statement, each Owner shall make a report in writing to the Administrative Owner of any dispute concerning such statement. Each Owner shall pay to the Administrative Owner any amount undisputed by such Owner stated in such statement within ten (10) Business Days. Any dispute concerning a statement shall be subject to the dispute resolution process stated in Section 10.1. Such payment shall be made by each Owner to the Administrative Owner in immediately available funds by electronic wire transfer, or by deposit otherwise made within ten (10) Business Days after resolution of the dispute, into the account designated in writing from time to time by the Administrative Owner for such purpose.
(b) Notwithstanding the provisions of Section 4.4(a) above, the Administrative Owner shall make available during regular business hours, for inspection and audit by each of the Owners, all books and records of the Administrative Owner relating to the amounts contained in each statement provided to such Owner pursuant to Section 4.4(a). Such books and records shall be retained by the Administrative Owner for such period as the Owners Committee may determine, but not less than the period provided for by the applicable Law, including any FERC guidelines; and such books and records shall be made available by the Administrative Owner for inspection and audit by each of the Owners during the Administrative Owners regular business hours. The costs and expenses of any inspection or audit requested by an Owner shall be borne by the Owner requesting such inspection or audit. Each Owner shall have the right to conduct such audits with respect to any statement for two (2) years following receipt of such statement.
(c) The Administrative Owner also shall permit any Owner to inspect the Common Facilities during regular business hours, provided that such Owner arranges such inspection with the Administrative Owner and complies with the safety requirements imposed by the Administrative Owner.
4.5 Sole Expenses of Each Owner. The following expenses shall be the sole obligation of Casselman and each Subsequent Party, respectively:
(a) Any replacement, removal or other capital expenditures with respect to the generation facilities or other separate improvements or equipment of such Owner for its Project and with respect to the Transmission Providers Interconnection Facilities and the Interconnection Customers Interconnection Facilities required in connection with its Project.
(b) Rent, turbine installation fees, solar panel installation fees, operating fees and other payments due to Landowners under the Shared Real Property Documents that are payable directly in connection with the ownership and operation of the energy generation facilities of such Owner.
(c) Any charges and damages due under the terms of the Shared Real Property Documents that are directly or indirectly related to (i) Casselmans use under the Shared Real Property Documents and (ii) each Subsequent Partys use under the Shared Real Property Documents and the Grants.
4.6 Limitation of Liability.
Neither the Administrative Owner nor the officers, directors, agents, and employees of the Administrative Owner shall be liable pursuant to this Agreement for actions performed solely as the Administrative Owner, except for acts or omissions constituting gross negligence, fraud, or willful misconduct. ARTICLE 5 : OWNERS COMMTTEE 5.1 Establishment of Committee; Voting. There is hereby established an Owners Committee to take all actions with respect to the Common Facilities, except as otherwise granted to the Administrative Owner pursuant to Article 4, and to take all other actions that all of the Owners may, from time to time, agree in writing that the Owners Committee is authorized to take in connection with the ownership (as applicable), rebuilding, operation, maintenance, repair, replacement and removal of the Common Facilities and the improvement and maintenance of the Shared Premises, or any portion thereof. Each Owner shall be entitled to appoint two (2) members to the Owners Committee, provided that no Owner shall be entitled to appoint or maintain a member on the Owners Committee unless that Owner has commenced operation of its Project and is using the Gen-Tie Line to transmit the output of its Project. The total number of members on the Owners Committee shall be equal to the product of two (2) times the number of Owners, unless unanimously agreed by the parties. Each member of the Owners Committee shall be entitled to cast one (1) vote. Each member of the Owners Committee shall have the right to cast such vote with respect to any decision, approval or other action to be made by the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement. If an Owners Committee member participating in a meeting of the Owners Committee does not vote either in favor of or against any matter subject to a decision, approval or other action of the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement, such member shall be deemed to have voted against it. Each decision, approval, or other action by the Owners Committee must be unanimous. A matter shall be deemed approved by the Owners Committee only if it shall have been approved by all of the votes of the Owners regardless of whether such Owners or their representative members on the Owners Committee are in attendance at the meeting. Consistent with each Owners interconnection agreement, FirstEnergy will be notified of any decision (A) to remove from service permanently or otherwise to dispose of the Gen-Tie Line, or (B) to make any capital expenditure for the purpose of increasing the Full Capacity of the Gen-Tie Line within thirty (30) calendar days of the Owners Committee approval.
5.2 Appointment of Members; Alternates. The members of the Owners Committee, as well as alternate members who may represent their respective Owners in the absence of the regular member, are identified on Exhibit E to this Agreement. Any Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively) may change its Owners Committee member by giving written notice of such change to each other Owner, and upon receipt of such notice the Owners shall revise Exhibit E to this Agreement accordingly. Any Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively), by giving written notice to each other Owner, may, for purposes of any decision, approval or other action to be made by the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement, appoint an alternate or alternates to serve on the Owners Committee in the place of, and to cast the vote of, the regular Owners Committee member appointed by such Owner.
5.3 Meetings. The Owners Committee shall meet regularly, but not less often than once each year, at such time and place as may be agreed upon by the members of the Owners Committee, and the Owners Committee shall meet at such other times and places as may be requested by any Owners Committee member by written notice to each other Owners Committee member at least thirty (30) days prior to such meeting. Members of the Owners Committee may participate in such meetings in person or by means of conference telephone calls, video conferences, or similar communications during which all persons participating in the meeting can hear each other. Participation in a meeting by means of conference telephone calls or similar communications shall be deemed to constitute presence in person at the meeting. Failure by any Owners Committee member to attend any annual or special meeting of the Owners Committee for which notice was properly given under this Section 5.3 shall not invalidate such meeting or any decisions, approvals or other actions taken at such meeting, and the non-attending member shall be deemed to have been present for purposes of a quorum and to have voted in favor of any matter subject to a vote by the Owners Committee at such meeting.
5.4 Decisions by Written Action. Any decisions, approvals and other actions that may be taken at a meeting of the Owners Committee may be taken without a meeting if all Owners Committee members consent thereto in writing. The Owners Committee may, by the unanimous vote of the members of the Owners Committee, adopt written procedures for review or approval of matters or for the taking of other actions concerning the Common Facilities.
5.5 Subcommittees. The Owners Committee may appoint such subcommittees as it deems necessary or appropriate and, by the unanimous vote of all of the members of the Owners Committee, may delegate approval authority to such subcommittees with respect to matters concerning the Common Facilities. Members of a subcommittee are not required to otherwise be a member of the Owners Committee.
5.6 Budgets. The Owners Committee shall have the authority to review and approve or amend the annual budgets and budget amendments prepared by the Administrative Owner pursuant to Section 4.2(b). If for any reason the Owners Committee does not approve an annual budget prior to the end of the eleventh (11th) month of the preceding operating year, the budget for such preceding operating year shall apply to operating year, subject to an increase or decrease in such budget to reflect the change in the GDPIPD for all goods and services during the twelve (12) month period ending with the tenth (10th) month of such preceding operating year. The Owners Committee shall have the authority to amend or replace any budget. 5.7 Emergency Actions. The Administrative Owner shall have the right but not the duty to proceed with an item that has been disapproved as provided in this Article, if the Administrative Owner determines in its reasonable judgment that such action is required to avoid an imminent threat of loss of life or property or is required to avoid an imminent threat of interruption of service over the Gen-Tie Line; provided, however, that if the Administrative Owner takes such action on a disapproved item and if the determination made in any subsequent review of the decision is that the item was not consistent with Prudent Industry Practice, then the Administrative Owner shall individually compensate the disapproving Owners for all of the net increase in cost or other financial impact of such action to the extent that it is inconsistent with what the reviewers determined would under such circumstances have met such test. 5.8 Tax Election. Each of the Owners shall, to the extent permitted by Section 761 of the Code, elect as provided in Treasury Regulation Section 1.761-2 to exclude from the provisions of Subchapter K of the Code any organization that they may otherwise comprise by virtue of this Agreement.
5.9 Commencement.
The terms of this Article V with respect to the Owners Committee shall become applicable and effective commencing on the occurrence of the first Sharing Effective Date with respect to a Subsequent Project. Prior to such time, Casselman shall continue to have and exercise all rights and responsibilities as the sole owner of the Common Facilities.
ARTICLE 6 : COVENANTS
6.1 Casselmans Covenants.
Casselman hereby covenants as follows:
(a) Casselman shall not permit any mechanics liens arising out of Casselmans use of the Shared Premises pursuant to this Agreement to exist against the Shared Premises. If Casselman wishes to contest any such lien, Casselman shall, within sixty (60) days after it receives notice of the lien, provide a bond or other security to each Subsequent Party as each Subsequent Party may reasonably request, or remove such lien from the affected property pursuant to applicable law.
(b) Casselman shall have the right, in its sole discretion and at its sole expense, in its name, or in its and each Subsequent Partys names jointly (but in such case only with advance notice to each Subsequent Party), to contest the validity or applicability to the Common Facilities or the Shared Premises of any law, ordinance, statute, order, regulation, property assessment or the like made by any governmental agency or entity that relates to the Casselman Wind Project or the Common Facilities. Casselman shall control any such contest and each Subsequent Party shall cooperate with Casselman in every reasonable way in such contest so long as Casselman does not seek relief adverse to any Subsequent Party, at no out-of-pocket expense to each Subsequent Party.
(c) Casselman shall perform its obligations under each of the Shared Real Property Documents in all material respects. Notwithstanding any provision of the Shared Real Property Documents that would allow Casselman to quitclaim or surrender the same or any portion thereof, Casselman shall either (at Casselmans sole discretion) (i) keep and maintain each Shared Real Property Document and Project Agreement in full force and effect for the full term thereof or (ii) quitclaim the same to each Subsequent Party. Subject to the terms and provisions of the Shared Real Property Documents, each Subsequent Party shall have the right, but not the obligation, to cure any default by Casselman the performance of any covenant, condition or agreement contained in any of the Shared Real Property Documents that could give rise to a termination of such Shared Real Property Document or Project Agreement by the applicable Landowner or counterparty thereunder, following at least ten (10) days written notice to Casselman. In the event of any such cure by a Subsequent Party, Casselman shall, upon demand, reimburse such Subsequent Party for all reasonable and verifiable out-of-pocket costs, fees and expenses (including reasonable attorneys fees and expenses) incurred by such Subsequent Party in effecting such cure. Upon receipt by Casselman of a written notice of default under any of the Shared Real Property Documents, Casselman shall immediately deliver a copy thereof to each Subsequent Party.
(d) Casselman shall reasonably cooperate with each Subsequent Party with respect to the interconnection, start-up and testing of its Subsequent Project Facilities.
6.2 Covenants of Each Subsequent Party.
Each Subsequent Party hereby covenants as follows:
(a) Such Subsequent Party shall not permit any mechanics liens arising out of its use of the Shared Premises pursuant to this Agreement to exist against the Shared Premises. If such Subsequent Party wishes to contest any such lien, it shall, within sixty (60) days after receipt of notice of the lien, provide a bond or other security to Casselman as Casselman may reasonably request, or remove such lien from the affected property pursuant to applicable law.
(b) Such Subsequent Party shall comply with Hazardous Materials Laws in connection with its separate activities on the Shared Premises, and agrees to indemnify Casselman against such Subsequent Partys violation of the Hazardous Materials Laws on the Shared Premises, including such violations by its agents or contractors.
(c) Such Subsequent Party shall have the right, in its sole discretion and at its sole expense, in its name, or in its and Casselmans names jointly (but in such case only with advance notice to Casselman), to contest the validity or applicability to the Common Facilities or Shared Premises of any law, ordinance, statute, order, regulation, property assessment or the like made by any governmental agency or entity that relates to its Subsequent Project or the Common Facilities. Such Subsequent Party shall control the contest and Casselman shall cooperate in every reasonable way in such contest so long as it does not seek relief adverse to Casselman, at no out-of-pocket expense to Casselman.
(d) Such Subsequent Party shall not take or fail to take any action, where such action or failure would constitute a default under, or would be materially inconsistent with the terms and provisions of, any of the Shared Real Property Documents; and it shall at all times materially comply with such terms and provisions. Such Subsequent Party hereby assumes and agrees to perform all obligations of Casselman under the Shared Real Property Documents to the extent such obligations are applicable to, and that would bind Casselman in connection with, such Subsequent Partys ownership and operation of its Subsequent Project on any portion of the Shared Premises, or the exercise, use or implementation of the Grants, which assumption shall be effective upon such Subsequent Partys compliance with the conditions described in Section 2.5.
(e) Such Subsequent Party shall install revenue meters at such locations as may be required to accurately measure output from its Subsequent Project that is delivered to the Lick Run Substation, or shall institute such other commercially satisfactory methods as may be required to measure the output from its Subsequent Project separately from the output of the Casselman Wind Project. With respect to the Summit Solar Project specifically, the Subsequent Party that owns the Summit Solar Project is responsible for all costs to procure and install the FirstEnergy high-side revenue meters required by the interconnection agreement for the Summit Solar Project and as shall be further described and detailed in the Interconnection Plans (the Additional Revenue Meters). 6.3 Covenants of All Parties. (a) Taxes. Each Party shall pay, when due, all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its facilities and/or operations subject to such Partys right to contest by appropriate legal proceedings the validity or applicability of any such taxes and assessments.
(b) Compliance with Law. Each Party shall, at its sole cost and expense, promptly comply with all applicable statutes, laws, ordinances, rules, regulations, orders and permits (collectively, Laws) and with all covenants, conditions and restrictions in effect during the term of this Agreement or any part thereof regulating the use of the Shared Premises or any facilities thereon; provided however, that such Party shall have the right to contest by appropriate legal proceedings the validity or applicability of any such Law. Each Subsequent Party hereby accepts the Shared Premises and each part thereof and the Grants subject to all such Laws, covenants, conditions and restrictions, and to any reservations, easements, liens, encumbrances and other matters affecting the Shared Premises or any part thereof that exist as of the Execution Date.
(c) Conduct of Activities. Each Party shall (a) conduct its operations and activities on the Shared Premises and each part thereof in accordance with sound and prudent engineering, operation and maintenance practices and Prudent Industry Practices, and (b) keep its facilities in good condition and repair, in good and efficient working order and in a safe condition. No Party shall conduct its operations or activities, or use or permit the use of the Shared Premises or any part thereof or its facilities in any manner that will create waste or a nuisance or that will damage the Shared Premises or any part thereof; and each Party shall be liable and responsible to the other Parties for any such waste, nuisance or damage.
ARTICLE 7 : INSURANCE
7.1 Insurance for Common Facilities.
(a) The Administrative Owner shall procure at the earliest practicable time and thereafter maintain in effect at all times hereinafter provided, to the extent such insurance is reasonably available at reasonable cost, under policies of insurance to protect and insure against: workers compensation and employers liability, where appropriate; commercial general liability for bodily injury and property damage; all risks of physical damage to the Common Facilities, including transportation and installation perils; automobile liability; and such other insurance as the Owners Committee may deem necessary.
(b) The Administrative Owner will name each Owner as an additional insured on the all risks property insurance required in Section 7.1(a) with respect to the Ownership Interests of each Owner.
(c) A copy of all policies of insurance procured by the Administrative Owner pursuant to Section 7.1(a) shall be provided to each Owner. The Administrative Owner shall notify each Owner in writing of (i) the assertion of any claim for bodily injury or property damage in excess of the deductible of one hundred thousand dollars ($100,000) or greater related to the Common Facilities immediately following the Administrative Owners knowledge of any such assertion and (ii) the Administrative Owners knowledge of the occurrence of an event likely, in the reasonable determination of the Administrative Owner, to result in the assertion of such a claim immediately following any such occurrence. If any loss, damage or impairment to the Common Facilities occurs, the Administrative Owner shall apply the proceeds of any insurance policy with respect thereto to repair, replace or restore the Common Facilities to their prior condition.
